text: Superman is a fantasy character. But this is really what would likely happen if he came to Earth. Everyone would either worship him, or try to kill him...but everyone would be scared shitless. Any display of super powers, and he would be arrested. If he refused, it would instantly escalate. Very soon, it would be the planet VS him. So far, this looks like a must see movie, especially if you are a comics fan. By the way, imagine you are a 12 year old kid that's bullied at school and you discover you have these godlike powers....any attempt to defend yourself, and people would be seriously hurt, and scared......and then you are a world threat. The only course of action would be to completely hide your abilities for your entire life.

text: CAPTAIN MARVEL ( FEMINIST) THE MOVIE: In 1995, on the Kree Empire's capital planet of Hala, warrior Vers suffers from recurring nightmares involving a battle and an older woman while training to join Starforce. Her mentor, Yon-Rogg, warns her to control her ability to fire photon blasts from her hands. When she loses her temper, Vers meets with the Supreme Intelligence, an artificial intelligence and the Kree's ruler, who offers the same warning.  Yon-Rogg leads Vers and fellow Starforce members Att-Lass, Bron-Char, Korath and Minerva to a planet infiltrated by the Skrulls, a race of alien shapeshifters that can perfectly simulate anyone, and with whom the Kree are at war. When attempting to extricate a captured spy, Vers is taken prisoner and subjected to a memory probe by the Skrulls' General Talos. Escaping with Talos and others in pursuit, she reaches Earth ‚Äî crashing through a Blockbuster Video store in Los Angeles. She rigs a communication device to contact Starforce, and her presence attracts police as well as S.H.I.E.L.D. agents Nick Fury and Phil Coulson. As they question her, they are fired upon by a Skrull in disguise. Vers pursues the alien, but after a fight aboard a train, loses him ‚Äî though not without recovering a crystal containing her disjointed extracted memories, which her lead her to a bar in a nearby town. Meanwhile Fury, driving after Vers, discovers a Skrull impersonating Coulson. The alien dies when Fury purposefully crashes the car. Fury follows a lead to the bar with Vers, while Talos impersonates Fury's boss, Keller.  Fury and Vers agree to work together, and using Fury's security clearance visit the secret air base Pegasus that appeared in Vers' deep memory along with the identity of the older woman, Dr. Wendy Lawson. They learn Lawson was a Kree, and died along with her pilot in a 1989 crash while flight-testing her light-speed engine ‚Äî and that the pilot was Vers. Avoiding capture by "Keller" and S.H.I.E.L.D. agents, Vers and Fury escape in a small cargo jet, with Lawson's cat Goose, adopted by the base, having stowed away. In Louisiana, Fury and Vers speak to Maria Rambeau, Vers' fellow jet pilot (callsign "Photon"), the last person to see Lawson and Vers alive. They fill each other in with the help of Maria's young daughter Monica, and Vers learns she was jet pilot Carol Danvers. Talos, who had tracked her, arrives and asks to speak. Using the black-box recorder of Lawson's crashed plane, Danvers learns an alien spaceship had shot it down ‚Äî and she now remembers Yon-Rogg killing Lawson, as well as Lawson's warning that the experimental engine's energy-core had to be destroyed to keep it from the wrong hands. Vers shot it and was caught in an ensuing explosion, with her body absorbing the energy. Yon-Rogg brought the amnesiac "Vers" ‚Äî the remaining portion of "Danvers" on her broken dog tag ‚Äî to Hala.  Talos explains the Skrulls are simply refugees, and Lawson's engine was to help them escape beyond Kree reach. Using coordinates Lawson had given Danvers, she, along with Fury, Monica, and Goose ‚Äî who for some reason terrifies Talos ‚Äî fly their Skrull-modified cargo jet to a cloaked ship in orbit. There they find the source of the energy-core's power, the Tesseract ‚Äî and some Skrull refugees, including Talos' mate and child. Yon-Rogg's Starforce, having tracked them, captures Danvers and places her in VR before the Supreme Intelligence. Enraged at being used, Danvers fights back, and discovers that a Kree implant that purportedly gave her Kree powers was instead limiting them. Accessing her full force, Danvers escapes, gives the Tesseract to Fury for safekeeping, and battles the Starforce to give Rambeau time to fly herself, Fury, and the Skrulls to Earth ‚Äî along with Goose, who is not a cat but an alien known as a Flerken that can sprout powerful tentacles and whose insides are a pocket dimension where the Tesseract is placed. Rambeau shoots down a pursuing Minerva. Danvers chases an escaping Yon-Rogg and discovers the extent of her powers, including flight. She singlehandedly destroys multiple ballistic missiles that Kree official Ronan the Accuser, called in by Yon-Rogg, has fired at Earth, and forces Ronan's forces to retreat. On Earth, Danvers quickly defeats Yon-Rogg and sends him back to Hala with a warning to the Supreme Intelligence.  Danvers agrees to help the Skrulls find a new homeworld, giving Fury a modified pager with which to contact her in an emergency. Fury later drafts a proposal for an initiative, changing the name after finding a photo with Danvers' old callsign of "Avenger".  In a present-day mid-credits scene, Danvers meet Avengers Steve Rogers, Natasha Romanoff, Bruce Banner, and James Rhodes, who were monitoring the pager Fury had activated. In an end-credits flashback, Goose coughs up the Tesseract.
author: Jared Cruz

text: I was never a fan of superhero films. As a kid, I felt they ignored logic too much, and basically insulted intelligence because it was a genre and concept that was somehow allowed to get away with so much. Spiderman, Hulk and Superman were my usual go-to when explaining my reasoning... and this is basically how I described it would really go down if an alien baby with extreme amounts of power was to be raised by humans in rural America. This is exactly what I spoke about when talking about Superman. I am very excited to see that someone else shares the more disturbingly likely scenario that I always imagined, but I was bullied for saying as I was either too nerdy, too depressing, or just felt that I was ruining things for the sake of it.

text: Could be interesting if the writing's good, but, once again the stereotype of the bullied kid turning evil gets played out by Hollywood, so that leaves me with my doubts. Look at the majority of serial killers, dictators, genocidal rulers. Notice what they all have in common? The ability to mask themselves as competent, often popular members of society. American Psycho is much closer to the mark in this regard.  Not saying the idea here is totally bad, it just relies to heavily on a really terrible Hollywood trope which does more to reinforce bullying. It'd be far more interesting if the character seemed normal to everyone else and we get to see their other side and their horrible rationalisations (or maybe they don't even have any) for their actions. This one's a hard pass for me at the cinema.

They could totally pull a Venom and make this a prequel to the Dark Superman arch type from the Injustice game that eventually rules the world. We could visit deep dogmas and zeitgeists throughout the film. It could be dark and gritty and beautiful and get us into the mind of a god.   Fingers crossed.

text: I'm definitely watching this movie! I love the premise. Although i can't get behind the idea of people calling him "evil". He's NOT evil. What would happen if you were bullied as a child by everyone at school, called a creep and even the teachers didn't try to help you? What if you suddenly discovered that you had super powers? In this scenario, can any of us honestly say they wouldn't get revenge? We, as normal humans, typically don't because we are weak. We can't fly, put our hand in a running lawnmower blade and not have it cut off, or effortlessly crush someones hand by taking it. Not to mention the laser eyes! I'm confident that regardless of what we say we would do in such a situation, EVERYONE would most likely use these powers for their own gain and soon wouldn't care about the greater good or humanities "justice". Besides, "good" and "evil' are points of view. People are extremely complex and attempting to define someone with a single word is just absurd. But i digress, this is going to be a great movie! So looking forward to it!!!

text: This is obviously a twist on the Superman Story, what if he would turn to bad?   The big difference here are  the adoptive and caring parents.  Martha and Jonathan Kent, in Superman's case,  they both instituted morals on his adoptive son.  There is an excellent scene in Man of Still when a young Clark Kent is overwhelmed by his out of control senses that he runs from his classroom and hides in a closet, he hears his classmates calling him a freak then his mother Martha came to help him get out of the closet.  With great powers comes great responsibility, remember who told that to Spiderman?  His uncle Ben, who was a good and honest man and Peter changed when he failed to save him by letting a delincuent scape when he could have stopped him.   In the TV series Smallville, a teen aged Clark Kent also spent a period of time abusing his power.  And here is the real problem:  Power corrupts, absolute power absolutely corrupts, so it would be easier to accept that a powerful human like alien would turn to bad rather than to good, because being good is hard and being bad is fun.  But this notion is getting out of hand in this depiction, bordeline in sadistic on this Brightburn movie. You see a protective mother which is logical coming from a woman who could not bear children.  There is also a scene where she tells him that he is a blessing, so you wonder what made him change into evil, to abuse his power when his mother seems very good.  Also the scene with the lawn mower it just is simply ridiculous, no one on his right mind would try to stop the blade with his hand, if you want to know if you are strong or bulletproof you would start with basics, a needle, a knife, hitting a wall, but what if you were wrong and while trying to stop the blade your fingers get cut off?  Ooops!

text: I don‚Äôt think anyone will read but I had some thoughts that I wanted to share . Some months before this trailer I kinda got interested in how horror had a lot of social implications ,from vampires to slasher movies they all had a social implication(even some of h.p lovecrafts works) this movie is one of the first artistic responses to mass-shootings (as far as I‚Äôm aware) and a genuine response to superhero movies and they go hand in hand pretty great because kids look up to superheroes more than anyone and superheroes are representatives of humanities best potential (so are kids) but we don‚Äôt really have a representative in humanities worst sides ( super villains are usually some guy for the superhero to beat metaphorically or literarily) this shows that kids potential can go either way and kids having power can be horrifying  Sorry for anyone who read that long

text: An idea for an evil Batman:  The son of a rich couple sees his parents been murdered by the Cosa Nostra (the villains in the Tim Burton movie). He later leaves to travel the world, looking for training. He eventually joining an order of Professional killers dedicated to deliver back alley justice. He desserts and uses his skills for vengeance rather than justice. The boy discovers a a taste for violence, and once his targets are dead, he decides to continue with all others.   Some have deducted his identity, but his power and influence made him untouchable. There is still someone willing to investigate his crimes, a war veteran turned detective.   The boy is now a man. He wares a dark costume and is usually silent.... except when he laughs like a demon clown.    The main inspirations would be Nemesis by Mark Millar, Patrick Bateman from American Psycho and the Batman who laughs.

text: This is basically how Smallville Season 8 depicted Davis Bloome as Doomsday to be.. He wasnt found by the Kents and raised with the same values as Clark aka Superman.. This is simply showing how even if the Kents had found Davis and raised him he'd still turn out as Doomsday destined to kill Clark. A sort of twisted Mirror Box type movie and I LOVE IT! text: Oooh, the prequel to BvS has arrived!  In all seriousness though, it‚Äôs funny how this is being hailed as something new and creative (and I‚Äôm really excited to see it!) when in many ways it is one of the more logical ends for a kid with superpowers?  Imagine growing up, being treated like a messiah figure by your parents. You weren‚Äôt born on earth so you likely grow up exhibiting likely aspergers or autistic-like symptoms, and when other kids start to bully you for it, you realize you have superpowers. You‚Äôre strong, you can fly, you can shoot lasers from your eyes. No other kid can do that. Mom always said you were special. You start dreaming of the place that you called home, memories creeping in. You were raised in a militaristic society. Blood and death defined your birth. Mom and dad lied to you. You‚Äôre not human, you never were. They start to realize you‚Äôre not human. They start to get scared, wondering if you‚Äôre a monster. A demon instead of an angel. So you start to wonder the same. You‚Äôre not human. You never were. So why do you have to follow their rules? Your people believed in war, believed in winning battles through bloodshed. Soon enough, you‚Äôre locking the doors to the school and blowing it up. You‚Äôre murdering the woman who called you a freak in the principal‚Äôs office. You‚Äôre chasing your father, and you‚Äôre chasing your mother.  They all deserve it. Because they lied. They called you a hero, a saviour, but why would you save the world when its people have shown you again and again that they‚Äôre just not worth it?

text: One thing that people complain about Superman is how he has no flaws in his powers which makes him boring. I think that Brightburn really shows how that isn‚Äôt necessarily the case. Superman may be incredibly strong and almost invincible, but one power that is always undervalued is his incredible self restraint. He always has to keep himself, both physically and mentally, in check so he doesn‚Äôt kill anyone. Imagine being angry and punching someone, they may get a bruise but that‚Äôs it. Now imaging channeling that same exact anger into a gun instead of a fist; the same anger can cause much more harm. That is what Superman has to worry about all the time. Almost all superhero movies do not effectively show how their powers negatively affect the innocent people around them. Most  movies just show the evil in other people and keep the heroes ‚Äúpure‚Äù. Brightburn shows that one of the most dangerous enemies can come from within.

text: The movie is okay, but at least one part made NO sense. *************Spoilers Follow***********************       He went to kill his aunt to stop her from telling the sheriff the bad things about him. And he is about to do it when interrupted by her husband and decides to kill him instead. He never even touches the aunt. THAT MAKES ZERO SENSE. She would STILL end up telling the sheriff about him. Killing the husband did NOTHING to stop her from talking to the sheriff. Only delayed it a little at best. Just stupid writing.   Also, "The Movie Spoiler" website synopsis said he is shown killing millions during the beginning of the credits. That is wrong! He isn't shown killing anyone. They simply showed ONE large building collapse and that was it as far as destruction is concerned. And that was clearly an actual controlled demolition of the building. Nothing about it indicated wanton mass slaughter as has been shown in many disaster movies. Anyway, if you want to leave right after the movie, go ahead, you won't be missing much.

text: SPOILERS   This movie has plot holes; one of which is (spoiler) that the kids mom tries to kill him with a piece of metal from the ship that brought him here. That's ridiculous and makes no sense, why would the aliens send him here in a ship built of a metal that could kill him!?  Also, this movie has lame moments when it becomes self aware and spoils the horror atmosphere its trying to create, using humor. In one scene the kid is being possesed or spoken to by an alien presence, he shakes like a boy possesed by demons, then the camera pans to a bobble head toy shaking its head! üòí  In the scene where the kid kills a man in a car, the guy playing the victim does the WORST ACTING and says lamest lines I've seen.  This film feels like the creators didn't really know what they wanted it to be. It could have been great if they turned it into a criminal thriller like Silence Of The Lambs, but the most interesting scenes in it just end up being over the top gore porn.  We don't feel much for Brandon because the motivations for him turning "evil" are so weak. He's a freak at school and a girl he likes found him creepy, is that enough to turn a child into a homicidal maniac? No. If they had had him experience some trauma or dangerous situation where he accidentally killed someone then developed a taste for it, that would have worked. Also his powers like invulnerability and super strength just suddenly happen, not like he was born with them.   People who want to see superman kill people might enjoy this, but the action scenes are the only real reason to watch this movie. Not a terribly interesting story.

text: This isn't just "Superman gone wrong," its his entire origin story flipped upside down.  It starts with the spaceship crashing in the woods in the dead of night, whereas in the Superman origin story, it crashes into an open field on a beautiful sunny day.  People make a lot of what the B and the backwards B in the symbol might stand for exactly, but suppose for a second that it's actually a B and a sideways W .  It's DC's "Earth 3," also known as "Bizarro World" (BW).  Awesome flick.

text: Worst GD'd so-called "Sci-Fi" movie in a long time. Why? Because it's just a series of gruesome killings perpetrated by an alien kid, no explanations of where he came from, or why he's so hostile, or why the parents are so nonchalant about it. Yeah, there's possibly a tiny hint from when the kid gives an answer in class about hornet reproduction, but what the hell does even that mean? And why is he such a freakin' genius? Is he the anti-Superman? Why? Why would any extraterrestrial race deposit a kid on Earth so randomly, if they have serious intentions of taking over? And what's here on Earth that's so very, very necessary for said ET's to take from us Earthlings? Very frustrating to watch, this is why I never pay to see a movie anymore, if I'd have paid to see this in a theater or as a pay-per-view, my language here would not have been so nice-nice!!! A little explanatory back story would've gone a long way, even more would've made this a great movie!!!

Massacring and slaughtering as they wish until they become literally our masters and us their slaves. The world literally in the hands of 6 or 7 individuals. That would rule unchallenged. Of course it wouldn`t hurt to also add a few superheroes that might be able to stand against them or alongside the aliens.
